node.statement: CASE 1b CONCLUSION: g_3(B) cannot equal B (by 1.10). g_3(g_2(B)) cannot equal g_2(B) either: If g_3(g_2(B)) = g_2(B), since g_3 is a cycle with {2,5} in g_2(B) intersect supp(g_3), by Lemma 11.2 supp(g_3) would be contained in g_2(B). But {3,6} is in supp(g_3) and {3,6} is in B which is disjoint from g_2(B). Contradiction. So g_3 moves both B and g_2(B) to different blocks. This means the orbit of B under <g_2,g_3> has size >= 3. Continuing this analysis: every generator moves B non-trivially except g_1. The orbit under H grows until it covers all of Omega, forcing |B| = N. CONTRADICTION.
